  "local_port": 45862,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you invert your selection in Photoshop?",
  "response": "Inverting a selection in Adobe Photoshop allows you to select everything **except** the currently selected area. This can be particularly useful for applying adjustments, masks, or effects to the areas surrounding your initial selection. Here's how you can invert your selection using various methods:\n\n---\n\n### **Method 1: Using the Menu Bar**\n\n1. **Create an Initial Selection:**\n   - Use any of the selection tools (e.g., **Marquee Tool**, **Lasso Tool**, **Quick Selection Tool**) to make your initial selection on the image.\n\n2. **Invert the Selection:**\n   - Navigate to the top menu and click on **`Select`**.\n   - From the dropdown, choose **`Inverse`**.\n\n   ![Select Inverse Menu](https://example.com/select-inverse-menu.png) *(Replace with actual image if available)*\n\n   - **Shortcut:** This method inverts your selection to include everything **outside** the initially selected area.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 2: Using Keyboard Shortcuts**\n\n- **For Windows:**\n  - Press **`Shift + Ctrl + I`** simultaneously.\n  \n- **For Mac:**\n  - Press **`Shift + Command + I`** simultaneously.\n\n  This instantly inverts your current selection without navigating through menus.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 3: Using the Context Menu**\n\n1. **Right-Click Inside the Selection:**\n   - After making your initial selection, right-click anywhere within the selected area.\n\n2. **Choose Invert:**\n   - From the context menu that appears, select **`Inverse`**.\n\n   ![Context Menu Invert](https://example.com/context-menu-invert.png) *(Replace with actual image if available)*\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips:**\n\n- **Feathering the Selection:**\n  - Before inverting, you can feather your initial selection to create smoother edges. Go to **`Select > Modify > Feather`** and input the desired pixel value.\n\n- **Using Layers and Masks:**\n  - After inverting the selection, you can apply a **Layer Mask** to non-destructively hide or reveal parts of your layer based on the inverted selection.\n\n- **Combining with Other Selection Tools:**\n  - Inverting selections works seamlessly with various selection tools, allowing for complex selections and edits.\n\n---\n\n### **Visual Guide:**\n\n1. **Initial Selection:**\n   ![Initial Selection](https://example.com/initial-selection.png) *(Replace with actual image if available)*\n\n2. **After Inverting:**\n   ![Inverted Selection](https://example.com/inverted-selection.png) *(Replace with actual image if available)*\n\n*(Note: Replace the placeholder URLs with actual images if you plan to include visuals.)*\n\n---\n\nBy using these methods, you can efficiently invert selections in Photoshop to enhance your photo editing workflow. Whether you're masking, adjusting colors, or applying effects, inverting selections provides greater flexibility and control over your edits.\n\n---\n\n**References:**\n- [Adobe Photoshop User Guide](https://helpx.adobe.com/photoshop/user-guide.html) \u2013 Official Adobe documentation for more detailed instructions and advanced techniques.",
